Power Rule

Fractional & Radical Exponents

Notes

Anything to the power of 0 is always 1.

When we have any base with an exponent of 0, the answer is always 1.

\[\begin{align} 0^{0} &= 1\\\\ 2^{0} &= 1\\\\ (\sqrt{3})^{0} &= 1\\\\ (-4)^{0} &= 1\\\\ (\frac{1}{5})^{0} &= 1\\\\ 9,999,999,999,999^{0} &= 1 \end{align}\]

Notes

Flip the base and its exponent vertically.

Example 1

\[\begin{align} 3^{-19} &= \text{?} \end{align}\]

Example 2

\[ \begin{align} \frac{1}{g^{-5}} &= \text{?} \end{align}\]

Example 3

\[\begin{align} \frac{1}{x^{3}} &= \text{?} \end{align}\]

When a base has a negative exponent, the term needs to the opposite side of the fraction.

If there is no fraction, write a 1 underneath first.

\[\begin{align}3\color{red}^{-4}\color{black} &= && \text{The exponent is -4 and the base is 3}\\\\ \frac{3\color{red}^{-4}}{\color{black}1} &= && \text{Write the base as a fraction}\\\\ &= \frac{1}{3\color{blue}^{4}}\color{black} && \text{Flip and make the exponent positive}\end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Write \(3^{-19}\) as a fraction without a negative exponent.

Explain

\[\begin{align} 3^{-19} &= && \text{The exponent is -19 and the base is 3}\\\\ \frac{3\color{red}^{-19}\color{black}}{1} &= && \text{Write the term as a fraction}\\\\ &= \frac{1}{3\color{blue}^{19}}\color{black} && \text{Flip the term and remove the negative from the exponent} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Write \(\frac{1}{g^{-5}}\) as a whole number without a negative exponent.

Explain \[\begin{align} \frac{1}{g\color{red}^{-5}\color{black}} &= && \text{The exponent is -5 and the base is g}\\\\ &= \frac{g\color{blue}^{5}\color{black}}{1} && \text{Flip the term and remove the negative from the exponent}\\\\ &= g\color{blue}^{5}\color{black} && \text{Simplify the answer} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Rewrite \(\frac{1}{x^{3}}\) with a negative exponent.

Explain \[\begin{align} \frac{1}{x\color{blue}^{3}\color{black}} &= && \text{The exponent is 3 and the base is x}\\\\ &= \frac{x\color{red}^{-3}\color{black}}{1} && \text{Flip the term and add a negative to the exponent}\\\\ &= x\color{red}^{-3}\color{black} && \text{Simplify the answer} \end{align}\]

Notes

Add the exponents, but only if the bases are the same.

Example 1

\[\begin{align} 5^{4}\cdot5^{9} &= ? \end{align}\]

Example 2

\[\begin{align} 18^{-14}\cdot18^{0} &= ? \end{align}\]

Example 3

\[\begin{align} a^{-4}\cdot (-a)^{5}\cdot a^{-5} \end{align}\]

The Product Rule tells us to add the exponents whenever 2 equal bases are being multiplied.

Here's an example:

\[\begin{align} 3^{5} \cdot 3^{3} &= && \text{The base is 3 while the exponents are 5 and 3}\\\\ &= 3^{\color{red}5 + 3\color{black}} && \text{Keep the base and add the exponents}\\\\ &= 3^{\color{red}8\color{black}} \end{align}\]

… but here's why:

\[\begin{align} \color{blue}3^{5}\color{black}\cdot\color{red}3^{3}\color{black} &= && \text{Rewrite the problem}\\\\ \color{blue}3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3\color{black}\cdot\color{red}3\cdot3\cdot3\color{black} &= && \text{Write out the multiplication}\\\\ 3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3 &= && \text{Suddenly it’s just 1 long chain of multiplication}\\\\ &= 3^{8} && \text{… and rewrite the repeated multiplication as an exponent} \end{align}\]

This pattern occurs whenever equal bases are being multiplied together. We are adding as a shortcut because this “chain” of repeating multiplication is getting longer.

Try this yourself first:

Rewrite \(5^{4}\cdot5^{9}\) as a single exponent. Do not find the product.

Explain \[\begin{align} 5^{4}\cdot5^{9} &= && \text{The base is 5 and the exponents are 4 and 9}\\\\ &= 5\color{red}^{4 + 9}\color{black} && \text{Rewrite the base and add the exponents}\\\\ &= 5\color{red}^{13}\color{black} && \text{Leave the answer as an exponent} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Rewrite \(18^{-14}\cdot18^{0}\) as a single exponent. Do not find the product.

Explain \[\begin{align} 18^{-14}\cdot18^{0} &= && \text{The base is 18 and the exponents are -14 and 0}\\\\ &= 18\color{red}^{-14 + 0}\color{black} && \text{Rewrite the base and add the exponents}\\\\ &= 18\color{red}^{-14}\color{black} && \text{Leave the answer as an exponent} \end{align}\]

Please note that ugly numbers do not change a thing.

Try this yourself first:

Simplify \(a^{-4}\cdot (-a)^{5}\cdot a^{-5}\) as much as possible.

Explain \[\begin{align} a^{-4}\cdot (-a)^{5}\cdot a^{-5} &= && \text{This is way too messy, so let’s reorganize it}\\\\ \color{red}a^{-4}\cdot a^{-5}\color{black}\cdot (-a)^{5} &= && \text{Rewrite with like terms next to each other}\\\\ \color{red}a^{-4 + (-5)}\color{black}\cdot (-a)^{5} &=&& \text{The 2 different bases are a and -a}\\\\ &= \color{red}a^{-9}\color{black}\cdot (-a)^{5} && \text{This is as far as we can go} \end{align}\]

Please note that a and -a are not like terms and cannot be combined.

The Quotient Rule tells us to subtract the exponents whenever 2 equal bases are being divided, which is shown by writing them as a fraction.

Here's an example:

\[\begin{align} \frac{3^{5}}{3^{3}} &= && \text{The base is 3 while the exponents are 5 and 3}\\\\ &= 3^{\color{red}5 - 3\color{black}} && \text{Keep the base and subtract the exponents}\\\\ &= 3^{\color{red}2\color{black}} \end{align}\]

… but here's why:

\[\begin{align} \frac{\color{blue}3^{5}\color{black}}{\color{red}3^{3}}\color{black} &= && \text{Rewrite the problem}\\\\ \frac{\color{blue}3}{\color{red}3}\color{black}\cdot \frac{\color{blue}3}{\color{red}3}\color{black}\cdot \frac{\color{blue}3}{\color{red}3}\color{black}\cdot \color{blue}3\cdot3\color{black} &= && \text{Write out the multiplication and line up as many factors as possible}\\\\ \color{red}1\cdot1\cdot1\color{black}\cdot\color{blue}3\cdot3\color{black} &= && \text{Some of the terms cancel out to 1, but not all of them}\\\\ &= 3\color{blue}^{2}\color{black} && \text{… and rewrite the remaining factors as an exponent} \end{align}\]

This pattern occurs whenever equal bases are being divided. We are subtracting as a shortcut because this “chain” of repeating multiplication is getting shorter.

Try this yourself first:

Rewrite \(\frac{4^{8}}{4^{3}}\) as a single exponent. Do not solve the exponent.

Explain \[\begin{align} \frac{4^{8}}{4^{3}} &= && \text{The base is 4 and the exponents are 8 and 3}\\\\ &= 4\color{red}^{8 - 3}\color{black} && \text{Rewrite the base and subtract the exponents}\\\\ &= 4\color{red}^{5}\color{black} && \text{Leave the answer as an exponent} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Rewrite \(\frac{x^{12}}{x^{-6}}\) as a single exponent. Do not solve the exponent.

Explain \[\begin{align} \frac{x^{12}}{x^{-6}} &= && \text{The base is x and the exponents are 12 and -6}\\\\ &= x\color{red}^{12 - (-6)}\color{black} && \text{Rewrite the base and subtract the exponents}\\\\ &= x\color{red}^{18}\color{black} && \text{Leave the answer as an exponent} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Rewrite \(\frac{g^{-4}}{g^{5}}\) as a single exponent. Do not solve the exponent.

Explain \[\begin{align} \frac{g^{-4}}{g^{5}} &= && \text{The base is g and the exponents are -4 and 5}\\\\ &= g\color{red}^{-4 - 5}\color{black} && \text{Rewrite the base and subtract the exponents}\\\\ &= g\color{red}^{-9}\color{black} && \text{Leave the answer as an exponent} \end{align}\]

The Power Rule tells us to multiply the exponents whenever we have a power raised to a power.

Here's an example:

\[\begin{align} (3^{5})^{3} &= && \text{The base is 3 while the exponents are 5 and 3}\\\\ &= 3^{\color{red}5 \cdot 3\color{black}} && \text{Keep the base and multipl the exponents}\\\\ &= 3^{\color{red}15\color{black}} \end{align}\]

… but here's why:

\[\begin{align} \color{blue}(3^{5})\color{red}^{3}\color{black} &= && \text{Rewrite the problem}\\\\ \color{blue}3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3 \text{ } \color{red}\cdot \text{ } \color{blue}3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3 \text{ } \color{red}\cdot \text{ } \color{blue}3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3 \text{ } \color{black} &= && \text{Write out the multiplication}\\\\ &= 3\color{red}^{15}\color{black} && \text{… and rewrite the repeated multiplication as an exponent} \end{align}\]

This pattern occurs whenever exponents are being multiplied together. We are multiplying as a shortcut because this “chain” of repeating multiplication is getting longer.

Try this yourself first:

Rewrite \((3^{5})^{2}\) as a single exponent. Do not find the product.

Explain \[\begin{align} (3^{5})^{2} &= && \text{The base is 3 and the exponents are 5 and 2}\\\\ &= 3\color{red}^{5 \cdot 2}\color{black} && \text{Rewrite the base and multiply the exponents}\\\\ &= 3\color{red}^{10}\color{black} && \text{Leave the answer as an exponent} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Rewrite \((7^{-14})^{\frac{1}{2}}\) as a single exponent. Do not find the product.

Explain \[\begin{align} (7^{-14})^{\frac{1}{2}} &= && \text{The base is 7 and the exponents are -14 and ½}\\\\ &= 7\color{red}^{-14 \text{ } \cdot \text{ } \frac{1}{2}}\color{black} && \text{Rewrite the base and multiply the exponents}\\\\ &= 7\color{red}^{-7}\color{black} && \text{Leave the answer as an exponent} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Rewrite \((x^{5})^{\frac{-1}{5}}\) as a single exponent. Do not find the product.

Explain \[\begin{align} (x^{5})^{\frac{-1}{2}} &= && \text{The base is x and the exponents are 5 and -½}\\\\ &= x\color{red}^{5 \text{ } \cdot \text{ } \frac{-1}{2}}\color{black} && \text{Rewrite the base and multiply the exponents}\\\\ &= x\color{red}^{\frac{-5}{2}}\color{black} && \text{Leave the answer as an exponent} \end{align}\]

Notes

Fraction:

The numerator is the exponent, the denominator is the index.

Radical:

The exponent is the numerator, the index is the denominator.

Example 1

\[\begin{align} 7^{\frac{1}{3}} &= \text{?} \end{align}\]

Example 2

\[\begin{align} g^{\frac{13}{9}} &= \text{?} \end{align}\]

Example 3

\[\begin{align} \sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}4]{h}\text{ }^{-7} &= \text{?} \end{align}\]

If an exponent is a fraction, we can rewrite it as a radical, and vice versa.

Fraction to Radical

\[\begin{align} 4^{\frac{\color{blue}3}{\color{red}5}}\color{black} &= && \text{The exponent is 3/5 and the base is 4}\\\\ &= \sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}\color{red}5]{4}\color{blue}\text{ }^{3}\color{black} && \text{The numerator 3 is the exponent, the denomator 5 is the index} \end{align}\]

Radical to Fraction

\[\begin{align} \sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}\color{red}7]{8}\color{blue}\text{ }^{-3}\color{black} &= && \text{The radicand is 8, the index is 7, and the exponent is -3}\\\\ &= 8^{\frac{\color{blue}-3}{\color{red}7}}\color{black} && \text{The radicand 8 is the base, the exponent -3 is the numerator, the index 7 is the denominator} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Write \(7^{\frac{1}{3}}\) as a radical.

Explain

\[\begin{align} 7^{\frac{\color{blue}1}{\color{red}3}}\color{black} &= && \text{The exponent is 1/3 and the base is 7}\\\\ &= \sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}\color{red}3]{7}\text{ }\color{blue}^{}\color{black} && \text{The numerator 1 is “invisible”, the denominator 3 is the index} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Write \(g^{\frac{13}{9}}\) as a radical.

Explain

\[\begin{align} g^{\frac{\color{blue}13}{\color{red}9}}\color{black} &= && \text{The exponent is 13/9 and the base is g}\\\\ &= \sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}\color{red}9]{g}\text{ }\color{blue}^{13}\color{black} && \text{The numerator 13 is the exponent, the denominator 3 is the index} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Rewrite \(\sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}4]{h}\text{ }^{-7}\) as a radical.

Explain \[\begin{align} \sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}\color{red}4]{h}\color{blue}\text{ }^{-7}\color{black} &= && \text{The radicand is h, the index is 4, and the exponent is -7}\\\\ &= h^{\frac{\color{blue}-7}{\color{red}4}}\color{black} && \text{The radicand h is the base, the exponent -7 is the numerator, the index 4 is the denominator} \end{align}\]

If an exponent is a fraction, we can rewrite it as a radical, and vice versa.

Fraction to Radical

\[\begin{align} 4^{\frac{\color{blue}3}{\color{red}5}}\color{black} &= && \text{The exponent is 3/5 and the base is 4}\\\\ &= \sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}\color{red}5]{4}\color{blue}\text{ }^{3}\color{black} && \text{The numerator 3 is the exponent, the denomator 5 is the index} \end{align}\]

Radical to Fraction

\[\begin{align} \sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}\color{red}7]{8}\color{blue}\text{ }^{-3}\color{black} &= && \text{The radicand is 8, the index is 7, and the exponent is -3}\\\\ &= 8^{\frac{\color{blue}-3}{\color{red}7}}\color{black} && \text{The radicand 8 is the base, the exponent -3 is the numerator, the index 7 is the denominator} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Write \(7^{\frac{1}{3}}\) as a radical.

Explain

\[\begin{align} 7^{\frac{\color{blue}1}{\color{red}3}}\color{black} &= && \text{The exponent is 1/3 and the base is 7}\\\\ &= \sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}\color{red}3]{7}\text{ }\color{blue}^{}\color{black} && \text{The numerator 1 is “invisible”, the denominator 3 is the index} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Write \(g^{\frac{13}{9}}\) as a radical.

Explain

\[\begin{align} g^{\frac{\color{blue}13}{\color{red}9}}\color{black} &= && \text{The exponent is 13/9 and the base is g}\\\\ &= \sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}\color{red}9]{g}\text{ }\color{blue}^{13}\color{black} && \text{The numerator 13 is the exponent, the denominator 3 is the index} \end{align}\]

Try this yourself first:

Rewrite \(\sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}4]{h}\text{ }^{-7}\) as a radical.

Explain \[\begin{align} \sqrt[\leftroot{-3}\uproot{3}\color{red}4]{h}\color{blue}\text{ }^{-7}\color{black} &= && \text{The radicand is h, the index is 4, and the exponent is -7}\\\\ &= h^{\frac{\color{blue}-7}{\color{red}4}}\color{black} && \text{The radicand h is the base, the exponent -7 is the numerator, the index 4 is the denominator} \end{align}\]
